<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Differential Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The differential is a key component of the drivetrain, responsible for distributing power from the engine to the wheels while allowing them to rotate at different speeds. This is essential for smooth turning and traction, especially on uneven surfaces.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Types of Differentials Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Types of Differentials</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Open Differential:</strong> Allows wheels to rotate at different speeds, commonly used in most vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Limited-Slip Differential (LSD):</strong> Provides better traction by distributing power to the wheel with the most grip.</li>
        <li><strong>Locking Differential:</strong> Locks both wheels together, ensuring they rotate at the same speed. Ideal for off-road vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Torsen Differential:</strong> Uses gears to automatically distribute torque between wheels, providing excellent traction.</li>
        <li><strong>Electronic Differential:</strong> Uses sensors and electronics to control power distribution, often found in modern and high-performance vehicles.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Components Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ring Gear:</strong> Transfers power from the driveshaft to the differential.</li>
        <li><strong>Pinion Gear:</strong> Connects to the driveshaft and drives the ring gear.</li>
        <li><strong>Spider Gears:</strong> Allow the wheels to rotate at different speeds during turns.</li>
        <li><strong>Axle Shafts:</strong> Transfer power from the differential to the wheels.</li>
        <li><strong>Differential Housing:</strong> Encloses and protects the internal components.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly check the differential fluid level and replace it as recommended by the manufacturer.</li>
        <li>Inspect the differential for leaks, cracks, or damage and repair or replace it if necessary.</li>
        <li>Listen for unusual noises (e.g., whining or grinding) that may indicate differential issues.</li>
        <li>Ensure the differential is properly lubricated to reduce friction and wear.</li>
        <li>Schedule periodic inspections to maintain the differential's performance and longevity.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Differential Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Differential Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Unusual Noises:</strong> Whining, grinding, or clunking sounds during turns or acceleration.</li>
        <li><strong>Vibrations:</strong> Excessive vibrations while driving may indicate differential problems.</li>
        <li><strong>Difficulty Turning:</strong> The vehicle may struggle to turn smoothly, especially at low speeds.</li>
        <li><strong>Fluid Leaks:</strong> Visible differential fluid leaks under the vehicle.</li>
        <li><strong>Uneven Tire Wear:</strong> Misaligned or malfunctioning differentials can cause uneven tire wear.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

